## Precipiation Patterns 
Precipitation does impact spatio-temporal movement patterns in a fairly heterogeneous way, indicating no clear relationship between precipitation and spatio-temporal movement patterns of students. 

However, some patterns were emerging as distances travelled were marginally longer and speed were slightly higher by bike, bus and car and students travelled longer by bike and car on days with heavy rainfall. In this context, it was shown, that when travel destinations are obligatory (e.g., work, lectures) people change their travel mode more likely under heavy rain, meaning that they drive to work instead of walk. However, if destinations are linked to leisure activities, people mor likely just postpone the task instead of changing their travel mode (Connolly,  2008;  Zivin,  2014) (Brum-Bastos et al., 2018). Additionally, during the week a decrease in public transport was observed under heavy rain by Brum-Bastos et al. (2018). 
This pattern could not be confirmed in the context of our research, as we only looked at days with or without high precipitation and did not include the type of activity and days of the week. Additionally, the results emerging from speed, distance and duration during rainy or dry conditions were fairly heterogeneous and no clear trends could be obtained. 

We found a slight decrease in walking speed and distance, while duration under heavy rain found was slightly higher, while Brum-Bastos et al. (2018) found an overall decrease in walking during rain. They also found a trend of more vehicular use under heavy rain (Brum-Bastos et al., 2018), which could no be confirmed in our research. 

However, it is unclear is those marginal patterns found in our data is indicative, as we only had a sample size of 5 students and investigated 11 days, from which 8 days were considered having heavy rainfall. Additionally, the results need to be interpreted with caution, as in fig. 11 it is shown, that for some trajectory points weather stations are rather far away to serve as indication for precipitation. 


